{"title_page": "Baghuwar, Madhya Pradesh", "text_new": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Baghuwar''', also pronounced Baghuvar (Devanagari: \u092c\u0918\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930), is a village located in the Kareli block of [[Narsinghpur]] [[district]] in the state of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]. The village is located under [[Jabalpur]] Division. It is approximately 201 km away from the state capital [[Bhopal]].\n\n==In The News==\nBaghuwar is known for its social ethics. Since [[Indian Independence Act 1947|India's independence on August 15th, 1947]], it is the only village in India where no Sarpanch is elected. Every house in the village is reported to have a [[toilet]] and there are [[sewage]] lines in the village. Baghuwar has the highest number of bio gas plants in the state, which is used for cooking [[food]] and for lighting up the village.<ref>{{cite web |title=15 Progressive Indian Villages That Will Make You Want to Ditch Your City Life Right Away! |url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/85354/inspiring-indian-villages-sustainable-development/ |website=thebetterindia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nThe hamlet with its population of 2400 worked collectively in transforming itself, seven years prior to the launch of the [[Swachh Bharat]] campaign by [[Prime Minister Narendra Modi]]. The villagers claim Baghuvar became Open Defecation-Free (ODF) in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=This small hamlet in Madhya Pradesh has a 100% literacy rate with the entire community having imbibed Mahatma Gandhi's teachings|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/this-village-in-madhya-pradesh-imbibed-bapu-s-teachings-became-odf-in-2004/story-nqScF7qKc6rgHaPO5k7rpL.html |website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> In 2012 the BBC reported that half the homes in India have phones but no toilets.[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-17362837]\n\n== Education ==\nThe village achieved a 100% literacy rate. The villagers firmly believes that every child is entitled to an education. Hence, they upgraded the school building with their own financial resources. They even ensured that healthy and nutritious mid-day meals were provided to the students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/115268/baghuwar-village-madhya-pradesh-sanitation-education/|title=With 100% Literacy and Total Sanitation, This MP Village is an Exemplary Example|date=2017-09-13|website=The Better India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Demographic ==\nThe Baghwar/Baghwar Census Location Code Number of 2001 is 04812000 and Census Location Code Number of 2011 is 491371. The village extends over a surface area of 906.7 hectares (3.5 square miles or 2240.5 acres). In 2011, the total [[population]] was of 1946 inhabitants for 465 households.<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/23/2335_PART_A_DCHB_NARSIMHAPUR.pdf |website=censusindia.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Agriculture==\nThe black [[soil]] found in the village is suited for most types of cultivation. [[Rabi crop|Rabi]] and [[Kharif crop|Kharif]] are the two seasons of cultivation here.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[latitude]] 23.24 and [[longitude]] 77.4 are the [[geocoordinate]] of Baghuwar. The local language is [[Hindi Language|Hindi]] which is used for communication. The [[PIN code]] of the village is 487221 & the [[telephone]] code is 07793.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geography |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=hIMLHC4Jl9M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding Villages==\nThe villages close to Baghuwar are - \n* Mohad\n* Amheta\n* Khiriya\n* Biner\n* Karoda\n* Bamhori\n* Amgaon\n* Barodiya\n* Tinsara\n* Simariya Khurd\n* Pipariya\n==References==\n\n[[Category:Villages]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh Villages]]\n[[Category:Indian Villages]]\n<references />\n", "text_old": "{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n'''Baghuwar''', also pronounced Baghuvar (Devanagari: \u092c\u0918\u0941\u0935\u093e\u0930), is a village located in the Kareli block of [[Narsinghpur]] [[district]] in the state of [[Madhya Pradesh]], [[India]]. The village is located under [[Jabalpur]] Division. It is approximately 201 km away from the state capital [[Bhopal]].\n\n==In The News==\nBaghuwar is known for its social ethics. Since [[Indian Independence Act 1947|India's independence on August 15th, 1947]], it is the only village in India where no Sarpanch is elected. Every house in the village is reported to have a [[toilet]] and there are [[sewage]] lines in the village. Baghuwar has the highest number of bio gas plants in the state, which is used for cooking [[food]] and for lighting up the village.<ref>{{cite web |title=15 Progressive Indian Villages That Will Make You Want to Ditch Your City Life Right Away! |url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/85354/inspiring-indian-villages-sustainable-development/ |website=thebetterindia.com}}</ref>\n\n==Population==\nThe hamlet with its population of 2400 worked collectively in transforming itself, seven years prior to the launch of the [[Swachh Bharat]] campaign by [[Prime Minister Narendra Modi]]. The villagers claim Baghuvar became Open Defecation-Free (ODF) in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=This small hamlet in Madhya Pradesh has a 100% literacy rate with the entire community having imbibed Mahatma Gandhi's teachings|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bhopal/this-village-in-madhya-pradesh-imbibed-bapu-s-teachings-became-odf-in-2004/story-nqScF7qKc6rgHaPO5k7rpL.html |website=hindustantimes.com}}</ref> In 2012 the BBC reported that half the homes in India have phones but no toilets.[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-17362837]\n\n== Education ==\nThe village achieved a 100% literacy rate. The villagers firmly believes that every child is entitled to an education. Hence, they upgraded the school building with their own financial resources. They even ensured that healthy and nutritious mid-day meals were provided to the students.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebetterindia.com/115268/baghuwar-village-madhya-pradesh-sanitation-education/|title=With 100% Literacy and Total Sanitation, This MP Village is an Exemplary Example|date=2017-09-13|website=The Better India|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n\n== Demographic ==\nThe Baghwar/Baghwar Census Location Code Number of 2001 is 04812000 and Census Location Code Number of 2011 is 491371. The village extends over a surface area of 906.7 hectares. In 2011, the total [[population]] was of 1946 inhabitants for 465 households.<ref>{{cite web |title=Demographic |url=http://censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/23/2335_PART_A_DCHB_NARSIMHAPUR.pdf |website=censusindia.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Agriculture==\nThe black [[soil]] found in the village is suited for any type of cultivation. [[Rabi crop|Rabi]] and [[Kharif crop|Kharif]] are the two seasons of cultivation here.\n\n==Geography==\nThe [[latitude]] 23.24 and [[longitude]] 77.4 are the [[geocoordinate]] of Baghuwar. The local language is [[Hindi Language|Hindi]] which is used for communication. The [[PIN code]] of the village is 487221 & the [[telephone]] code is 07793.<ref>{{cite web |title=Geography |url=https://www.indiapost.gov.in/VAS/Pages/LocatePostOffices.aspx?Pin=hIMLHC4Jl9M= |website=indiapost.gov.in}}</ref>\n\n==Surrounding Villages==\nThe villages close to Baghuwar are - \n* Mohad\n* Amheta\n* Khiriya\n* Biner\n* Karoda\n* Bamhori\n* Amgaon\n* Barodiya\n* Tinsara\n* Simariya Khurd\n* Pipariya\n==References==\n\n[[Category:Villages]]\n[[Category:Madhya Pradesh Villages]]\n[[Category:Indian Villages]]\n<references />\n", "name_user": "DavidThornbee", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed English grammar and added conversion of hectares to sq miles and acres.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baghuwar,_Madhya_Pradesh"}
